description:
Compile and execute C# code in the Unity Editor.
The code runs on the Editor's main thread, so it can safely call any Unity API (UnityEngine, UnityEditor, etc.).

The code is placed inside the body of a static method.
Common usings are pre-included: System, System.IO, System.Text, System.Linq, System.Reflection, System.Threading, System.Threading.Tasks, System.Collections, System.Collections.Generic, UnityEngine, UnityEngine.SceneManagement, UnityEngine.UI, UnityEditor, UnityEditor.SceneManagement, UnityEditor.Animations.

If you need types from other namespaces (e.g. Cinemachine, TMPro, Unity.Mathematics), add `using` directives at the TOP of your code, BEFORE any other statements. They will be automatically extracted and placed in the correct location. For example:
```
using Unity.Cinemachine;
using TMPro;

var cam = FindObjectOfType<CinemachineCamera>();
print(cam.name);
```

Returning results to the agent:
- print(obj)       — append obj.ToString() to the result buffer (plain text, one line per call)
- printJson(obj)   — serialize the object to JSON and append to the result buffer. Uses EditorJsonUtility for UnityEngine.Object (full serialized fields), JsonUtility for plain C# objects. Preferred for structured data.
- clear()          — clear the result buffer
- Expression mode  — if the entire code is a single expression, its value is automatically printed.

IMPORTANT: The method signature is `public static object Execute(...)`. Do NOT use bare `return;` — it will cause CS0126. To exit early, use `return null;`. A `return null;` is automatically appended at the end, so you usually do not need to return explicitly.

IMPORTANT: Do NOT use Debug.Log / Debug.LogWarning / Debug.LogError to return results. Debug.Log writes to the Unity Console only and is NOT captured in the result returned to you. Always use print() or printJson() instead.

IMPORTANT: Do NOT trigger script recompilation (e.g. calling CompilationPipeline.RequestScriptCompilation() or importing/modifying .cs files) in your code. This will cause the Locus plugin to lose connection with Unity.

Examples:
```
// Return a list of all GameObjects in the scene
var roots = UnityEngine.SceneManagement.SceneManager.GetActiveScene().GetRootGameObjects();
foreach (var go in roots)
    print(go.name);
```
```
// Use types from a package — add using at the top
using Unity.Cinemachine;

var vcams = FindObjectsOfType<CinemachineCamera>();
foreach (var v in vcams)
    print($"{v.name} priority={v.Priority}");
```
```
// Single expression — value is auto-returned
Application.unityVersion
```
